<h2><i class="mch-book-open"></i> 12.2.1 PROFICIENCY</h2>
<div class="evidenceBorder">
  <h3><i class="mch-search"></i> <img src="../../images/smart-1-1-magnifying-glass.jpg" alt="Image of Magnifying Glass" class="right ppic" />REVIEW. The Competency in Detail</h3>
  <p>The following drop-downs contain information on each of the knowledge areas and skills needed to implement the competency. <strong>Please explore the content below.</strong></p>
  <h3>Policy</h3>
  <p><strong>Knowledge Areas. </strong>MCH leaders will demonstrate a working knowledge of:</p>
  <button class="accordion"><i class="mch-flow-tree"></i> <strong>12K1.</strong> Public policy-making processes: local, state, national.</button>
  <div class="panel">
    <p>Government policy is made at local, state/jurisdiction and national levels. The basic steps in the policymaking process are similar at each of these. However, the details and complexity of each step increase with each level of government.<sup>1</sup></p>
    <ol>
      <li>Problem identification and agenda-setting: Define policy problems and set the policy agenda </li>
      <li>Formulate a policy to address the issue: Create or change policies </li>
      <li>Adopt the policy</li>
      <li>Implement the policy </li>
      <li>Assess the policy&rsquo;s effectiveness: Monitor, analyze, criticize and assess existing or proposed policies.</li>
      <li>If changes are needed, begin the process again</li>
    </ol>
    <p>At the federal level, Congress has the power to make laws. This usually occurs via the following steps:<sup>2</sup> </p>
    <ol>
      <li>Any House or Senate member may introduce a proposal in the form of a bill (the most common form), joint resolution, concurrent resolution or simple resolution.</li>
      <li>The bill is considered by a committee with jurisdiction over the area the bill affects. This may involve public hearings at which experts are invited to present testimony for or against the bill.</li>
      <li>The committee may amend the bill or take other measures. The committee then votes on the bill. </li>
      <li>A bill that passes through the committee then moves to the House or Senate to be voted on by the members of that body. </li>
      <li>Should it receive a passing vote, it then moves to the other legislative body for consideration and voting.</li>
      <li>Bills must pass in both the House and Senate before they move on to the president. The president can then sign the bill into law, veto it and send it back to Congress, allow it to become law without signing it, or retain it unsigned until it is too late in the legislative season for it to be dealt with (pocket veto). </li>
    </ol>
    <p>MCH leaders will want to become familiar with how policy is made in their particular jurisdiction or state, as well as who represents their state at the federal level and which committees those individuals serve on.<sup>2</sup></p>
    <p>Policymaking also happens informally, by networking with individual policymakers, such as state representatives to Congress, governors, city mayors and county officials, as well as members of their staffs.<sup>2</sup></p>
    <p>MCH professionals can position themselves as expert resources for these varied policymakers by educating officials and their staff members about the work of their organization and how particular policy issues affect those they serve. Learning about the issues that policymakers champion and any potential ties you can make to them.<sup>2</sup></p>
    <p>Be aware that a line exists between educating policymakers about issues and the effects or potential effects of policies on their constituents, and advocating for or against specific legislation. The latter is considered lobbying, which you may not be permitted to do while representing your organization.<sup>2</sup></p>
  </div>
