     <button class="accordion"><i class="mch-device-desktop"></i> <strong>12K3.</strong> Methods for informing/educating policymakers.</button>
  <div class="panel">
    <p>First, frame the policy question: What is the problem and what is the solution? </p>
    <p>Then, identify the research that supports that solution. Be clear and careful about sharing evidence-based information in an objective manner: Show the research, but do not overstate the evidence.</p>
    <p>To help policymakers, translate research into policy, preferably in a brief, jargon-free format. Prepare brief and compelling materials (e.g., fact sheets, policy briefs, and talking points). Keep this information up to date and within easy reach of your audience.</p>
    <p>Include personal stories about patients/clients whenever possible; these stories are qualitative in nature, but they give policymakers a personal connection and help them understand the impact of the policy they are considering. Ask patients/clients for permission to share their stories with legislators or encourage them to do so personally.</p>
    <p>Research your audience and offer tailored resources, including data, outcome measures, and your expertise. If a policymaker asks a question and you do not immediately have an answer, saying &ldquo;I don&rsquo;t know&rdquo; is fine. Tell the policymaker that you will look into it and e-mail or call back.<sup>3</sup></p>
    <p>Understand the line between advocacy and lobbying. </p>
    <ol>
      <li>Advocacy is intended to educate policymakers about an issue or an organization and its work. </li>
      <li><a href="https://ballotpedia.org/Lobbying">Lobbying</a> is aimed at affecting the outcome of specific legislation. Two forms of lobbying are defined by federal law and are regulated in certain circumstances.<sup>4</sup> </li></ol></div>

     <button class="accordion"><i class="mch-bullhorn"></i> <strong>12K4.</strong> Strategies for public communication.</button>
  <div class="panel">
    <p>Communication strategies aim to change people's knowledge, attitudes, and/or behaviors. They can, for example:<sup>5</sup></p>
    <ul>
      <li>Increase risk perception</li>
      <li>Reinforce positive behaviors</li>
      <li>Influence social norms</li>
      <li>Increase availability of support and needed services</li>
      <li>Empower individuals to change or improve their health conditions</li>
    </ul>
    <p>Strategic communication planning involves the following steps in some form:<sup>6</sup></p>
    <ul>
      <li>Identify the health problem and determine whether communication should be part of the intervention.</li>
      <li>Identify the audience for the communication effort and determine the best ways to reach them.</li>
      <li>Develop and test communication concepts, messages and materials with representatives of the target audiences.</li>
      <li>Implement the health communication plan based on testing results </li>
      <li>Assess how effectively the messages reached the target audience and modify the communication plan if necessary</li>
    </ul>
    <p>To improve how effectively a communication plan advances MCH priorities, it should include:<sup>5</sup></p>
    <ul>
      <li>Research-based strategies to shape materials and products and to select the channels that deliver them to the intended audience</li>
      <li>Conventional wisdom, concepts, language, and priorities for different backgrounds and settings</li>
      <li>Consideration of health literacy, internet access, media exposure and the cultural competency of target populations</li>
      <li>The use of a variety of media, including brochures, billboards, newspaper articles, television broadcasts, radio commercials, public service announcements, newsletters, pamphlets, videos, digital tools, case studies, group discussions, health fairs, field trips, and workbooks among others</li>
    </ul>
  </div>
 
  <p><strong>Skills</strong></p>
  <p><strong><em>Foundational. </em></strong><em>At a foundational level, MCH leaders will be able to:</em></p>
  <button class="accordion"><i class="mch-graph"></i> <strong>12S1.</strong> Frame problems based on data.</button>
  <div class="panel">
    <p>The problem is the gap between an acceptable or desirable health status and the current status.<sup>7</sup></p>
    <p>1. To frame a problem, write a problem statement.<sup>7</sup></p>
    <p>You will need to briefly answer these questions about the problem:</p>
    <ul>
      <li>What should be occurring? What is occurring?</li>
      <li>Who is affected and to what degree?</li>
      <li>What could happen if the problem isn&rsquo;t addressed?</li>
    </ul>
    <p>To answer these questions, you will need to use data from a variety of sources, such as:</p>
    <ul>
      <li><a href="https://www.cdc.gov/public-health-gateway/php/public-health-strategy/public-health-strategies-for-community-health-assessment-data-benchmarks.html?CDC_AAref_Val=https://www.cdc.gov/publichealthgateway/cha/data.html">Sources of community-level indicators from the CDC</a></li>
      <li><a href="https://www.childhealthdata.org/home">Data Resource Center for Child &amp; Adolescent Health</a> includes data and resources for Title V programs and partners</li>
      <li><a href="http://guides.library.cornell.edu/c.php?g=241897&p=1608179">Finding Health Data and Statistics: Getting Started</a>, a library guide from Cornell University</li>
      <li><a href="https://ephtracking.cdc.gov/">Environmental Public Health Tracking Network System</a> from a variety of national, state, and city sources</li>
      <li><a href="https://www.pewsocialtrends.org/">Pew Research Center Social and Demographic Trends</a></li>
      <li><a href="https://www.cbpp.org/">Center on Budget and Policy Priorities</a></li>
      <li><a href="https://news.gallup.com/topic/politics.aspx">Gallup Politics</a></li>
    </ul>
    <p>2. List and map the causes of the health problem.<sup>7</sup></p>
    <p>Consider the following:</p>
    <ul>
      <li>Genetic or biological factors</li>
      <li>Psychological factors</li>
      <li>Behaviors</li>
      <li>Factors in the physical environment (e.g., a lack of transportation)</li>
      <li>Factors in the social environment (e.g., social support, or policy)</li>
    </ul>
    <p>Categorize the causes: as direct and indirect, and as risk and protective factors. Weigh the factors and determine which ones are the primary factors.</p>
    <p>Determine which of these can change as a result of programmatic action (e.g., a social marketing program can&rsquo;t eliminate genetic risk factors).</p>
    <p>3. Identify potential audiences.<sup>7</sup></p>
    <p>Grouping the audience into meaningful segments will allow you to design efficient, effective strategies for reaching them.</p>
    <p>Determine which audiences are:</p>
    <ul>
      <li>Most affected by the problem</li>
      <li>Most likely to change their behavior</li>
      <li>Most feasible to reach</li>
      <li>Key secondary audiences</li>
    </ul>
    <p>Avoid making audiences too broad. It is a better use of your resources to impact fewer in a more meaningful way.</p>
    <p>Be sure to add to the list target audiences your program is required to reach, and additional audiences that could help bring about change.</p>
    <p>4. Conduct a SWOT analysis.<sup>7</sup></p>
    <p>A <a href="https://ctb.ku.edu/en/table-of-contents/assessment/assessing-community-needs-and-resources/swot-analysis/main">SWOT (Strengths, Weaknesses, Opportunities and Threats) analysis</a> assesses the factors in the broader situation that could impact the implementation of your program or its ultimate success.</p>
  </div>
  <button class="accordion"><i class="mch-list-ordered"></i> <strong>12S2.</strong> Use evidence in proposing policy change.</button>
  <div class="panel">
    <p>When proposing policy change, you will want to present the reasoning behind your proposal. This involves evaluating the current policy and the one you are proposing so that you can make the case for why a change is needed.</p>
    <p>Evaluation relies on a combination of data and values to determine the merit of a policy. Evaluative criteria specify the values that will be used in an evaluation.<sup>8</sup> The evaluative criteria that you select will depend on the type of policy you are evaluating. </p>
    <p>The following eight criteria may be helpful when evaluating a proposed policy:<sup>9</sup></p>
    <ul>
      <li>Effectiveness: To what degree does this particular policy attain its objectives?</li>
      <li>Efficiency: What are the results in relation to resource expenditure of the policy?</li>
      <li>Balanced Health Outcomes: How fair or just is the distribution of the policy&rsquo;s cost, benefits and risks across population groups?</li>
      <li>Liberty/freedom: To what extent will the policy restrict or extend privacy and individual rights and choices?</li>
      <li>Political feasibility: How likely are elected officials to support the proposed policy change?</li>
      <li>Social acceptability: How likely is the general public to support the proposed policy change?</li>
      <li>Administrative feasibility: How likely is it that the agency or organization can carry out the proposed policy change or program?</li>
      <li>Technical feasibility: Is the technology available to implement the proposed policy change?</li>
    </ul>
  </div>
  <button class="accordion"><i class="mch-users"></i> <strong>12S3.</strong> Distinguish roles and responsibilities of groups involved in public policy.</button>
  <div class="panel">
    <p>In the United States, the executive, legislative, and judicial branches of government are the primary bodies involved in developing and implementing policy. These branches are supposed to carry out the laws, make the laws, and interpret the laws, respectively.<sup>10</sup></p>
    <p>However, other groups are involved in policymaking as well, including interest groups representing specific causes or industries, and coalitions of organizations that have come together in support of &mdash; or against &mdash; a particular issue. </p>
    <p>Though it can be complicated and lengthy, the policymaking process follows several set steps:<sup>11</sup></p>
    <ul>
      <li>Recognize a problem: The problem should be something that legislation can address.</li>
      <li>Set an agenda: Decide which aspects of the problem or problems should be addressed first.</li>
      <li>Formulate the policy: All the stakeholders in a new policy come together to create the policy.</li>
      <li>Adopt the policy: This step can potentially take place before a legislative body or in a court of law. Once a policy has been created, it must be formally accepted by lawmakers, or ruled on by a judge or group of judges (in the Supreme Court), or signed into law by executive order of the President. </li>
      <li>Implement the policy: Agencies in the executive branch generally do the work of putting policy into place and enforcing it. However, this may also happen by judicial ruling.</li>
      <li>Evaluate the policy: After a policy has been in place for a length of time, legislators or other interested parties will check its effectiveness. Any problems arising from the policy will be addressed in a new round of the policymaking cycle. </li>
    </ul>
  </div>
    
  
 
  <p><em><strong>Advanced.</strong> Building on the foundational skills, MCH leaders will be able to:</em></p>
  <button class="accordion"><i class="mch-balance-scale"></i> <strong>12S4.</strong> Apply standards to evaluate alternative policies.</button>
  <div class="panel">
    <p>Analyzing alternative policies requires applying each of the evaluative criteria to each alternative in succession.<sup>12</sup></p>
    <p>As previously mentioned, evaluative criteria include:</p>
    <ul>
      <li>Effectiveness: To what degree does this particular policy attain its objectives?</li>
      <li>Efficiency: What are the results in relation to resource expenditure of the policy?</li>
      <li>Balanced Health Outcomes: How fair or just is the distribution of the policy&rsquo;s cost, benefits and risks across population groups?</li>
      <li>Liberty/freedom: To what extent will the policy restrict or extend privacy and individual rights and choices</li>
      <li>Political feasibility: How likely are elected officials to support the proposed policy change?</li>
      <li>Social acceptability: How likely is the general public to support the proposed policy change?</li>
      <li>Administrative feasibility: How likely is it that the agency or organization can carry out the proposed policy change or program?</li>
      <li>Technical feasibility: Is the technology available to implement the proposed policy change?</li>
    </ul>
    <p>Select a criterion, define it, and determine how it will be measured. Then consider the outcome if nothing is done, and the outcome if a particular policy alternative is enacted.<sup>12</sup></p>
    <p>This involves forecasting, or predicting the impact that the policy alternative would have in terms of achieving the relevant goals, and valuing the predicted impacts (quantitatively, qualitatively and/or monetarily). Forecasting methods can be simple or complex.</p>
    <p>Forecasting methods include:<sup>12</sup></p>
    <ul>
      <li>Intuition: <a href="https://www.healthknowledge.org.uk/public-health-textbook/research-methods/1c-health-care-evaluation-health-care-assessment/use-delphi-methods">Delphi</a>, <a href="https://otexts.com/fpp2/scenarios.html">scenario writing</a>, or <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Feasibility_study">feasibility assessment</a></li>
      <li>Theoretical models: These identify important variables, how they are linked, and then are used to predict outcomes when one of the variables is changed.</li>
      <li>Extrapolation: This method uses the past to predict the future. It is most often used when there are linear patterns in the data, and assumes that conditions are stable and variables will remain unchanged moving forward. </li>
    </ul>
    <p>Consider whether the predicted outcomes meet the desired goals. This may allow some alternatives to be quickly discarded.</p>
    <p>For each alternative policy:</p>
    <ul>
      <li>Show strengths and weaknesses. </li>
      <li>Describe the best- and worst-case scenario. </li>
      <li>Use matrices, reports, lists, charts, scenarios, and arguments to compare and contrast.</li>
    </ul>
    <p>MCH leaders will then need to weigh the results of the analysis to select the policy alternative that best fits.</p>
  </div>
  <button class="accordion"><i class="mch-chart"></i> <strong>12S5.</strong>  Analyze impact of policies on population groups.</button>
  <div class="panel">
    <p>It&rsquo;s important to know if the policy in question has different effects on various groups, such as those of different ages, genders, socioeconomic status, ethnicity, religion, residence in certain zones, sexual orientation, disabilities and similar.<sup>13</sup></p>
    <p>It's also important to know if the policy will reduce, create or increase differences among groups. It can happen that a policy appears to be effective on average, but in reality deepens health outcome variations between groups, with some benefiting much more and others much less. </p>
    <p>Differences in outcomes, combined with the effectiveness of a policy, and its unintended effects, impact the acceptability of a policy to the stakeholders involved.</p>
    <p><strong>How to Analyze Impact</strong><br>
      To gather information to assess the potential for a policy to impact risk factors, quality of life, morbidity and mortality among population groups, ask the following:<sup>14</sup></p>
    <ul>
      <li>How does the policy address the problem or issue (e.g., increase access, protect from exposure)?</li>
      <li>What are the magnitude, reach, and distribution of benefit and burden (including impact on risk factor, quality of life, morbidity and mortality)?
        <ul>
          <li>What population(s) will benefit? How much? When?</li>
          <li>What population(s) will be negatively impacted? How much? When?</li>
        </ul>
      </li>
      <li>Will the policy impact health variations/balanced health opportunities? How?</li>
      <li>Are there gaps in the data/evidence base?</li>
    </ul>
    <p>The above questions form one part of the full policy analysis process. (<a href="https://www.cdc.gov/polaris/php/policy-resources-trainings/key-policy-analysis-questions.html">View these additional questions</a> as well as a <a href="https://www.cdc.gov/polaris/media/pdfs/2024/09/Table2.pdf">scorecard</a> to use when analyzing one or more policies.)</p>
  </div>
    
    <button class="accordion"><i class="mch-checklist"></i> <strong>12S6.</strong> Formulate strategies to balance stakeholder interests.</button>
  <div class="panel">
    <p>It is important for MCH professionals to be able to understand and engage stakeholders. </p>
    <p>You should assess your stakeholders&rsquo; influence on and interest in your policy/project.<sup>15</sup></p>
    <ul>
      <li>Influence refers to how powerful a stakeholder is; this power may come from the position they occupy (elected or appointed official, job status), their status within a community (a community elder, clergy, or longtime volunteer), or their economic resources (wealthy donor, prominent community business).</li>
      <li>Interest refers to those stakeholders whose needs and interests coincide with the aim of the project.</li>
    </ul>
    <p>It&rsquo;s important to have stakeholders themselves explain their interests in your prospective policy or project, rather than assuming you know what they are. Reach out to as many stakeholders as possible to hear their views &mdash; even those who aren&rsquo;t willing to participate formally in your meetings or activities.<sup>16</sup> </p>
    <p>These questions may be helpful to ask stakeholders:<sup>15</sup></p>
    <ul>
      <li>What are the contributions the stakeholder can give to the policy/project and what resources are they likely to commit (or avoid committing) to the project?</li>
      <li>What interests does the stakeholder have in the policy/project? How might it benefit them?</li>
      <li>What are the stakeholder expectations of and requirements for the policy/project?</li>
      <li>What other interests does the stakeholder have that may conflict with the policy/project?</li>
      <li>What actions can be taken to address the stakeholder's interests?</li>
    </ul>
    <p>Once you&rsquo;ve gathered as much information about stakeholder interests as possible, conduct a stakeholder analysis (also known as stakeholder mapping). Stakeholder mapping helps various teams discuss the stakeholder politics that will influence their ability to plan together on how to navigate complex relationships.<sup>16</sup></p>
    <ul>
      <li>Create a four-quadrant graph that maps your stakeholders&rsquo; influence and interests. </li>
      <li>Starting from the top left quadrant and moving clockwise, assign each quadrant the following labels: high influence, low interest (latents); high influence, high interest (promoters); low influence, high interest (defenders); low influence, low interest (apathetics). Interest runs low to high on the vertical axis, and influence runs low to high on the horizontal axis.</li>
      <li>Place your stakeholders on the graph according to your assessment of their influence and interest.    </li>
    </ul>
    <p>You can begin to create a strategy for balancing stakeholders&rsquo; interest (i.e., engagement) and involvement in your policy/project based on this graph.<sup>15,16,17</sup> </p>
    <ul>
      <li>Promoters (high influence, high interest) should receive the bulk of your attention and be the most involved in your policy/project. They are essential to the success of your effort.</li>
      <li>Don&rsquo;t assume that latents (high influence, low interest) do not need to be or will not want to be involved in your project at some point; these stakeholders can wield their power to change your plans should their interest be piqued and they decide to become involved. They should be carefully monitored and managed.</li>
      <li>Defenders have high interest but little power to help your initiative. You should keep them informed of your progress, but you should not have to actively manage them.</li>
      <li>Apathetics are low-priority stakeholders who should be monitored, but who likely won&rsquo;t require much management. </li>
      <li>Outline the extent of cooperation and/or conflict you expect between stakeholders.</li>
      <li>Manage and coordinate arrangements to promote stakeholder ownership and participation, and avoid conflicts of interest.</li>
      <li>Create a plan for how you will communicate with each group of stakeholders, particularly with those who fall within the &ldquo;promoters&rdquo; category.</li>
      <li>Assign authority and responsibility for the major parts of the project. Consider creating a <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Responsibility_assignment_matrix">responsibility assignment matrix</a> (also known as a RACI matrix) to clarify roles and responsibilities among stakeholders.</li></ul></div>
    
     <button class="accordion"><i class="mch-podium"></i> <strong>12S7.</strong> Present evidence to decision makers/the public.</button>
  <div class="panel">
    <p>Policymakers, key decision-makers, foundations and the general public have some unique characteristics.<sup>18</sup></p>
    <ul>
      <li>Policymakers generally focus on the financial implications of a subject or policy, rely on gatekeepers to filter their information, look for certainty from experts, and make decisions intuitively.</li>
      <li>Key decision-makers, particularly those from grantmaking foundations, may have a particular focus for their activities and will want to understand how your work aligns with theirs.  </li>
      <li>The general public will vary in their educational attainment, socioeconomic status, health beliefs, social beliefs and worldviews.</li>
    </ul>
    <p>However, when presented with evidence and information, they share the same expectations:<sup>18</sup></p>
    <ul>
      <li>To be told why they should believe or do what you recommend</li>
      <li>To be given the rationale for how you reached your conclusions. Pre-existing beliefs and other factors can cause people to not be convinced to change their thinking without a sound and logical rationale for doing so</li>
      <li>To know what to do with the information they receive: what action they or others should take</li>
    </ul>
    <p>When presenting data, use the following tips to help connect with your audience:<sup>18</sup></p>
    <ul>
      <li>Avoid terms not frequently used outside of the scientific community, or those with multiple meanings.</li>
      <li>Explain how the data may impact audiences.</li>
      <li>Avoid science and math concepts that can be misunderstood. If these terms or concepts must be used, be sure to explain them in an easy-to-understand way.</li>
    </ul>
    <p>Overall, when delivering your message:<sup>18</sup></p>
    <ul>
      <li>Be brief and quickly get to the main point.</li>
      <li>Focus on the main message instead of detailed scientific arguments or outcomes.</li>
      <li>Avoid technical jargon </li>
      <li>Use real-world examples and localize data and narratives.</li>
      <li>Anticipate opposition arguments and be prepared with responses. </li>
    </ul>
  
  </div>
  
    
